data.content:
Yes — for simple inline values, use `[DataRow]` directly. It's type-safe, concise, and gives better test names:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Reserve `[DynamicData]` for when test data is complex (objects, collections) or generated at runtime. For those cases, you can improve type safety with tuples:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
    new (string Input, bool Expected)[]
    {
        ("valid@email.com", true),
        ("invalid", false),
        ("", false),
    }.Select(t => new object[] { t.Input, t.Expected });
```

**`[DataRow]`** is the best fit here — simpler, type-checked at compile time, and each row shows clearly in test output.
